<LEADPARA>  WHY AREN'T THERE THREE SEXES? Or a hundred sexes? Why are there just two
sexes?;   WE'VE BEEN TRYING TO IMAGINE what a third sex would look like.
Michael Jackson, maybe?  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  West  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THAT'S WHY
SEX: ONE OF THE GAMES GAMETES PLAY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     What exactly is a "male," anyway? Other than an organism that takes out the
garbage? The answer is: an organism with lots of tiny, motile gametes. That's
right! Men have incredibly small gametes, not that they'd ever admit to it. A
female produces large gametes. Eggs, basically. Gametes are sex cells. A human
female is born with a couple of million gametes, but during her lifetime only
about 400 of them come into play. A male produces billions of gametes (sperm).
This pattern -- one sex producing a few big sex cells, the other producing
zillions of small ones -- exists throughout the biological world.;   The
reason there's not a third sex is that two sexes are plenty enough to make
life complicated. Sexual reproduction on the planet seems to be designed to
mix up genes and recombine them. This variability allows the process of
natural selection to sort through genes, reward the well-adapted, punish the
geeks, and keep evolution cranking. You can get an almost infinite combination
of genes through two sexes, so there's no advantage in having a third sex.;  
Some species have only one sex, and they reproduce just fine by
parthenogenesis. The mothers spit out daughters that are genetic duplicates --
clones. An aphid, for example, can start an infestation of your garden all by
itself -- it reproduces by cloning. Some types of geckos employ
parthenogenesis, too. (Parents who are squeamish about telling their kids
where babies come from should just talk about "the geckos and the aphids.");  
Cloning doesn't allow for much genetic variety, and so sex is a more common
way to reproduce. But many species are hermaphroditic. They are both male and
female. Many flowering plants are hermaphrodites. So why aren't we all
hermaphroditic? Wouldn't that be a lot less of a hassle?;   The answer is: If
you possess both sexual characteristics, sometimes you will fertilize
yourself. This can create genetic defects. "You can pay a severe penalty for
self-fertilization," warns Brian Charlesworth, professor of ecology and
evolution at the University of Chicago. So be careful what you do with
yourself. You could go blind.  </TEXT>
