<DESCRIPT>  TRAVEL; ISLAND; OCEAN  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  BY NOW, even the polyester set must know the last trace of romance in this
tropical playground was long ago trampled to dust by hordes of stocky figures,
draped in bright new batiks, from Germany, the United States and Australia.;  
Kuta is to Australia, in particular, what Acapulco is to the United States,
and for some time now, even its fattest local merchants have looked forward to
time off when they can flee the daily nightmare of motorcycle exhaust, rowdy
drunks and gaudy shops with names like "Ego" and "Bad."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BALI-HYPE
MUCH OF THE ROMANCE IS GONE, BUT AMID THE LOUD
TOURISTS AND SHAMELESSLY HUSTLING NATIVES, A TRACE
OF BEAUTY CAN STILL BE FOUND  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story; Additional information attached to the end of this article  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Worse yet, now even the tourists are fleeing in droves from Kuta's
overcrowding, spreading the plague of frantic commerce throughout Bali.
There's hardly a remotely appealing beach or rice field that, in Noel Coward's
words, "does not recoil from suntan oil and the gurgle of Coca-Cola." Even in
Lovina, all the way on the northern coast, one can now buy playful,
anatomically correct dolls of the kind favored by Dan Quayle.;   Come to Bali
expecting pristine nature -- and natives -- and you'll leave Bali depressed.
By now, most intercultural experiences are cash-on-the-line.;   That said, the
surprise is that Bali still has enough elusive grace, outside Kuta, to merit
exploration. It takes patience, energy, a sense of humor -- but as ever, not
much money.;   Arriving for a three-week visit in July, my husband, Jack, and
I were initially horrified by the over-saturation of Large Loud White People.
The horror was greater, however, for Jack, a traveler of consummate political
correctness who likes his vacations in places like Nicaragua's Corn Islands
(under the Sandinistas) and Brazil's remote Fernando de Noronha, a kind of
mini-Galapagos where you cower, nightly, from exotic and probably venomous
bugs in your lodgings in private homes. I confess my own dismay in Bali was
soon tempered by eating lots of cheap, delicious satays and staying in
tranquil, immaculate bungalows where handsome Balinese men roused us from
sleep with steaming Java, fresh papaya and honey-drenched banana pancakes.;  
Fragrant bargains; Still, even in Kuta, we soon discovered pleasures not
explicitly designed to extract dollars. Dodging the motorcycles downtown, we
caught whiffs of cloves, frangipani and incense, surviving like half-forgotten
dreams beneath the clouds of carbon dioxide, and watched women in bright
sarongs wend their way through traffic to place offerings of flowers and fruit
at busy intersections. Bali, the exception in Indonesia's mostly Muslim
archipelago, is predominantly Hindu, and filled with intricate stone-carved
temples. On Kuta's busiest streets, stone deities on temple gates gaze blankly
at hordes of passing tourists, stumbling out of surfer taverns. They must be
wondering, just as Coward once wondered, "What compulsion compels them, and
who the hell tells them, to drag their cans to Zanzibar, instead of sitting
quietly in Omaha?";   The newer Poppies cottages (there are two sets) provided
refuge and consolation after a stroll along the beach, which I not only had to
pay for, but where one woman cursed me and all my ancestors and potential
offspring after I politely declined to buy a massage. The hotel is small and
refined, with the thatched-roofed cottages surrounding a garden and swimming
pool decorated with statues of imps.;   Mick's marriage; After a day, it was
time to move on. We paid a private driver $15 (about $5 too much) for a
90-minute journey to the inland village of Ubud, stopping on the way in Mas,
the nearby wood-carving village.;   Ubud, at first, carried bitter reminders
of Kuta. Friends had raved about its beauty and quiet -- Mick Jagger had even
gotten married there -- but the village has grown so quickly in the past two
years that inns, shops and restaurants now jam Monkey Forest Road, the
principal thoroughfare, and the revving of motorcycle engines is heard late
into the night.;   Nonetheless, we soon found Ubud was worth some lingering,
especially after a room opened at the Ulun-Ubud cottages, an inn about three
miles up from the monkey forest and far from the hubbub. The cottages cling to
a cliff overlooking the deep gorge of the Campuhan river and terraced rice
fields. By night, geckos sang us to sleep.;   By day, we took walks along the
stunning green rice terraces surrounding the village, watching duck shepherds
tend their flocks, and, one day, thousands of herons returning by twilight to
their forest. (Even there, we found the obligatory crafts stand, next to a
sign reading, "Best Place to View the Herons.") We also strolled through the
monkey forest, the domain of a large, aggressive tribe of apes.;   A Genuine
Contact;   One afternoon, having strayed far from Ubud's tourist core, we were
passing a temple in the rice fields when a sweet-faced young man with a flower
behind his ear asked us, in rough English, over to his house. Following the
man, Wayan -- the given name for a family's first child -- I could barely
contain myself; we were about to have a Genuine Contact with a Balinese. We
hiked to his home, far into the forest. He gave us tea, and then hustled us
unmercifully to buy some of his wood carvings.;   On other days, we spent
shameful amounts of time in restaurants. Ubud is crowded with peaceful cafes
where you can dine in splendor on Indonesian curries, seafood or even lasagna
with banana wine or the more straightforward arak for the equivalent of $2 or
$3. We also consumed several hours searching for the perfect shadow puppet.;  
Had we not been so busy taking naps on our terrace, we would surely also have
explored Ubud's much-praised museums and meditation center, and I would have
returned to Mas to take a mask-carving class.;   From Ubud, we hired a car for
the two-hour drive north to Lake Batur, which is to backpackers what Ubud is
to jet-setters. We stayed at the Art Center in the village of Toya Bungkah,
where a very basic but clean room cost us $20, and where we stumbled on a
local dance troupe of young girls led by a brilliant male teacher, rehearsing
Legong dances. It cost nothing to watch and was enchanting.;   The next day,
at 4 a.m., we set out with a guide, a broken flashlight and a bottle of water
to climb Mount Batur, the active volcano that towers over the lake. Our guide
entertained us almost the entire time by singing one off-key verse from
"Clementine.";   By sunrise, 5,000 feet and 2 1/2 hours later, we had just
made it to the top, to watch the spectacular play of orange and amethyst light
breaking over the lake, and Mount Abang, facing us. We could also see the tip
of Mount Rinjani on nearby Lombok Island, poking through clouds across the
sea. After the trip down, we soothed our aching joints in the hot springs near
the lake, where a troop of single-minded little girls massaged my shoulders,
then insisted I buy over-priced biscuits.;   Soon, two weeks had gone by. We
were both tired of being money belts with legs. So we boarded a dilapidated
ferry for a four-hour journey across the Java Sea to Lombok. Indonesia's
government would have been pleased: In the past few years, even Jakarta has
begun to recognize that Bali is over-visited, and has campaigned to get
tourists to explore other islands.;   Arriving late in the evening, we had
time for only glimpses of the island, with its starkly different atmosphere --
much poorer and more hard-bitten than Bali. We checked into the enormous
Sengiggi Beach Hotel, the government's most determined tourist project on
Lombok, and immediately regretted it. A 155-room enclave of bland modernity,
it was also inexcusably overpriced ($85 for a tiny cottage and mini-bar). Jack
began to mutter and didn't stop until the next morning, when we found a driver
and took off for Bangsal Harbor, to catch a prahu, a traditional outrigger
boat, bound for the tiny coral atoll of Gili Air, off Lombok's northwest
coast.;   Gili Air was the ticket: clear green water for snorkeling amid blue
and white coral forests, utter quiet, but for the periodic prayer calls of the
muezzins, and spectacular sunsets. And the best: lodgings we both loved. Most
accommodations on the island are simple, thatched-roof bungalows on stilts,
with Asian toilets and showers outside. But walking on the coast, we came
across a sign advertising a house for rent. The bungalow was large and lovely,
furnished in Balinese chic, with a garden in the bathroom and a wide,
bamboo-curtained terrace facing the sea. Three times a day, a shy Malay cook
named Su'ad, straight out of Joseph Conrad, would appear wordlessly with
elaborate and tasty meals. All for $25 a day.;   We would have retired then
and there but for the sudden appearance of the owner, a German shock
therapist, with half a dozen guests and twice as many suitcases. We were cast
out, and -- the cruelest shock of all -- we heard him mention, as we left, how
he and his brother intend soon to build a whole complex of cottages along Gili
Air's coast.; If you go . . .; (check) Travel Information; High season is all
year around, but the dry season is generally from April to September. No visa
is required for a stay of less than two months throughout Indonesia.
Immigration agents will, however, ask to see a passport and a return ticket.; 
 Indonesia's national airline, Garuda, has a direct flight from Los Angeles to
Denpasar, Bali. If that is booked and you need to shop around, Community
Travel in Berkeley, (415) 653-0990, can probably get discount flights.;  
(check) LODGING -- In Kuta Beach, a Poppies cottage can be reserved by calling
62-361-51059, or writing P.O. Box 378, Denpasar 80001, Bali, Indonesia. The
rate for a double-room thatched cottage with hot water and air-conditioning is
$56 plus 15 percent tax. In Ubud, the Ulun-Ubud cottages can be reserved by
writing P.O. Box 333, Denpasar, Bali 80001. Rates are $55 for a
double-occupancy bungalow and $85 for a suite. Includes breakfast. Also in
Ubud are the new Pringga Juwita Water Garden cottages, where you can rent
spacious and exotic two-story, open-air bungalows for $55.;   (check) ETC. --
Lonely Planet's "Indonesia: A Travel Survival Kit" ($19.95) is a terrific
guide for Bali and other islands, but we found it strikingly out of date in
parts.;   The recipe for Su'ad's banana pancakes: 5 bananas, 1 cup flour,
honey to taste, 1 egg, 1 cup water.; -- Katherine Ellison  </TEXT>
