<LEADPARA>  IF CHRISTOPHER Columbus had seen the cabins of the Bayman Bay Club nestled in
the lush hillside when he anchored in the azure waters off the island of
Guanaja in the summer of 1503, he might never have returned home.;   The
pristine hideaway on the north side of this 28-square-mile Honduran island
might have remained the explorer's secret.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HERE'S THE ULTIMATE IN DIVE RESORTS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Destination: Honduras; Additional information attached to the end of this
article.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Fortunately for those seeking a tranquil refuge or scuba diving that
borders on the spiritual, the Bayman Bay Club opened in 1975, long after
Columbus came and went. Late that year, former Green Beret Tom Fouke opened
his dream resort on 10 acres of tropical hillside.;   The somewhat laborious
trek to reach the island and the relatively spartan club accommodations should
keep this divers' haven from being overrun. No AC. No AT&amp;T. No cars. No way;
there's no road.;   With 15 cabins, the club accommodates only 30 guests a
week, anyway. (In case of emergency, the club has a radio. If you must take
care of business a fax machine is available in Bonocca, a town built on a sand
spit off the south side of the island and reachable by water taxi.);   The
cabins are charming -- and roomy. They boast hot water, comfortable double
beds and ceiling fans. Jalousie windows allow for cross-ventilation. (A
curtain, by the way, serves as the bathroom door.) The porches offer sweeping
bay and coastal vistas. All the cabins are connected by wooden walkways to the
main building and the club's 200-yard-long beach.;   Bayman Bay is not to be
confused with Club Med-style resorts that offer an array of non-stop
activities from archery lessons to theatrical productions.;   The Bayman Bay
logo should be a scuba tank resting in a hammock; hammocks, swings and sofas
beckon from covered porches and the shade of mango and gumbo limbo trees.
Social life revolves around the open-air, four-story main building, which
resembles something out of "The Swiss Family Robinson.";   Two single-tank
boat dives are offered daily at 9 a.m. and 2 p.m. There were never more than
16 divers on the 42-foot "Nimitz," a converted houseboat, which performs
adequately in its new role.;   Non-smokers will applaud the no-smoking sign on
board. Club staffers lug the tanks on and off the boat. Additional tanks are
available in the dive shop for unlimited shore diving day and night. Dive site
depths range from 20 feet just off the dock, a favorite haunt of a trio of
spotted eagle rays, to the 110-foot deep home of the wreck "Jado Trader," a
200-foot-long freighter. Summer water temperatures were consistently in the
low 80s.;   Many of the dive sites are only minutes away and appropriately
named: Wonderful Reef, Fabulous Reef, the Pinnacle. The kaleidoscopic Jim's
Silver Lode, a long chute teeming with glistening silversides, which empties
out to a sheer coral wall, also lives up to its name.;   The most fascinating
diving, however, was at night at a sight called Alderson's Wall. (The daylight
dive there was far from ho-hum.) Shine a light and watch coral feeding on
schools of hundreds of tiny worms; catch hefty spiny lobster and orange coral
crabs high-stepping across the lunar-like landscape; discover bright scarlet
lady shrimp and hand-sized banded coral shrimp hiding in crevices.;   Aside
from diving or vegetating, guests can take a short boat trip up the coast or
hike up a verdant, boulder-strewn jungle trail to a waterfall simply named The
Waterfall. The uphill climb is only for the hardy. The serenity and the cool
natural pool at hike's end are reward for making the trip.;   There are some
catches to visiting this slice of paradise.;   A love of animals and tolerance
of insects and reptiles are helpful. Harmless, palm-size geckos perch
everywhere, including cabin walls and ceilings. Much larger but shy iguanas
sun themselves on rocks and tree branches. Parrots begin squawking shortly
before 7 a.m. (a natural alarm waking guests in time for breakfast).; If you
go . . .; (check) Diving Packages -- Seven-night diver packages are $750 and
include three meals a day, two one-tank boat dives a day, unlimited shore
diving -- day and night -- tanks, weights and weight belt, a beginner's course
for non-divers, a beach picnic on a neighboring cay, a hiking trip, an evening
trip to the town of Bonocca and transfers from Guanaja's airport to the club.
The non-diver rate is $700. Group packages are available for nine or more
guests.;   Arrivals can be arranged for any day of the week. Sunday arrivals
are more expensive because they require chartering a plane from mainland
Honduras.;   (check) TRANSPORTATION -- Round-trip air fare from Miami to the
Honduran capital of Tegucigalpa is $358 on American Airlines. (Connecting
flights are also available from Houston on Continental. Honduran carrier
Tansahsa Airlines departs from Houston and New Orleans.) The Honduran Islena
Airlines ferries guests from Tegucigalpa to Guanaja for an additional $70
round trip. A passport is required.;   (check) INFORMATION -- Call the Bayman
Bay Club at (800) 524-1823.  </TEXT>
