<HL> Priest Electrifies a Philippine Farm Town --- Critics Question Unorthodox Way He Runs Cooperative </HL>
<AUTHOR> Mary Williams Walsh (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> FREST </CO>
<IN> UTI BIO </IN>
<DATELINE> DUMANJUG, the Philippines  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the sun goes down on this hardscrabble farm town, the lights start to flicker among the cornstalks and banana leaves. 

   There are 40-watt bulbs in lonely palm-leaf huts, fluorescent halos on plywood ceilings, illuminated roadside Coca-Cola signs. 
And everywhere there are tiny red Christmas bulbs lighting shrines to the local patron saint. 
The Rev. Francisco Silva, the man responsible for it all, has dedicated the past decade to the biblical command, "Let there be light." 

   "He is Mr. Electric Cooperative," says Emilio Osmena, governor of the surrounding province. 

   Father Silva, the Roman Catholic parish priest, runs two of the most efficient rural electric cooperatives in the Philippines. 
While other co-ops serve as money-losing dumping grounds for politicians' unemployed friends, Father Silva lights up the shanties of Dumanjug with a skeleton staff, pays his debts on time, and loses less than 10% of his power to breakdowns and pirates. 
Nationwide, the average is 35%. 

   Despite his robust results, Father Silva's unorthodox management style troubles auditors and U.S. aid officials. 
He urges his staff to sing on the job. 
He makes his constantly traveling truck drivers sign two-year chastity vows so they don't become lonely or despondent over romantic relationships while away from home. 
He has deputized coconut-wine gatherers -- who typically scale some 30 palm trees a day -- as low-paid, auxilliary tree-clearing crews. 
He begins each day with group prayers, and then dispatches his bill-collectors to the streets with carbines and orders to shoot to kill -- when necessary. 

   "Those who don't know me very well feel that I'm a dictator," he admits. 

   Rural electric cooperatives are an American invention, brought to the Philippines two decades ago by the U.S. Agency for International Development. 
From bolts to power-pole design, they mimicked the Rural Electrification Administration, in hopes that the system that powered New Deal America's farmhouses would serve these outlying islands just as well. 

   But like many American innovations grafted onto the Philippines, the co-ops didn't take very well. 
Some became launching pads for would-be politicians. 
Others gave free power and cash handouts to their boards. 
Of the 118 co-ops in the Philippines today, 79 lose money. 
Some are so broke they can't even provide rubber gloves or wirecutters to their linemen. 
Father Silva says some of these linemen must bite through wires with their teeth. 

   "Rural electrification co-ops are really a form of grassroots democracy," says Father Silva, sitting in fluorescent-tube splendor on his back porch one evening, while insect-eating geckos scamper just outside the pool of light. 
"But our culture isn't democratic." 

   Philippine society is rigidly hierarchical, with an elite whose members wouldn't dream of paying their utility bills. 

   "To them, disconnection is the height of disrespect," says Father Silva. 

   Members of the elite get their congressmen to write letters explaining that they don't have to pay. 
If an uppity co-op tries to disconnect one anyway, the matter can go to court and drag out for years. 

   Father Silva was running a school when the first electric co-op came to Dumanjug in 1972. 
Villagers danced in the streets at the news that electric light would be coming to their homes, he recalls. 
But before it erected a single utility pole, the new co-op spent two years building its own administration complex -- complete with floodlit tennis courts and the smoothest concrete roads in the village. 
The villagers' delight turned to discouragement. 

   Things only got worse when the lights came on. 
Management scrimped on maintenance. 
Two-way radios were purchased but never installed. 
Those that were installed didn't work. 
With no phones in Dumanjug, linemen had no idea where faults were. 
Blackouts lasted weeks. 

   Worse, management delayed staff paychecks. 
Underpaid installation crews turned to extorting bribes in exchange for service. 
Bill collectors pocketed payments. 
Demoralized dollar-a-day construction crews took whole days off at the slightest spatter of rain. 
By 1981, the co-op was so far behind in its payments that its supplier, the national power grid, threatened to shut it down. 

   That's when Father Silva joined up. 

   "I injected the faith factor," he says. 
"When I came in, I said, 'All your sins are forgiven. 
I want you to begin a new life.'" 
He followed the homily with tough rules. 
The next staffer caught stealing -- who happened to be the nephew of three other priests -- was fired. 

   Next, Father Silva banned drinking on construction sites. 
He installed floodlights, announcing that workers who took rain days would have to work their eight hours at night. 
When some malcontents sneaked onto a dam construction site after hours and threw rocks in protest, Father Silva gathered the stones, built an altar, tied it with black cloths, and said mass, heaping curses on the stone-throwers. 
The protests stopped. 

   To create a mandate for bill-collection, Father Silva held a referendum and the villagers voted to disconnect non-payers. 
Father Silva then offered his disconnection crews "combat hazard pay" and bought them carbines. 

   The acid test came last year when a non-paying policeman marched into the co-op, flung a .45-caliber pistol onto the desk and announced he would kill anyone who cut off his power. 

   "That's very common in the Philippines," says Father Silva. 
"Policemen will go into bars, drink and dance, and they don't pay. 
They get into cabs, show their badges and they don't pay." 

   The priest and his team went to the offender's house. 
"I was trembling like hell," Father Silva recalls. 
Guns at the ready, his men climbed the pole and shut off the power. 
The policeman brandished his pistol, but nothing happened. 

   Father Silva says he later preached a one-hour sermon on the disconnection. 
The gist, as he puts it now, was: "Every life is sacred, but we have a job to do here." 
He adds: "If it comes to killing in fulfillment of our duties, then I will do it." 

   With techniques like that, Father Silva's co-ops boast the highest collection rate in the co-op system. 
His staff has pulled in so much money that it used the surplus to open a subsidiary -- a coconut-log sawmill. 
Now, staffers are thinking about going into prawn farming. 

   Yet, not everyone is a convert. 

   "I have mixed emotions about this whole thing," says a USAID official who worries about some of Father Silva's techniques, including his guns and his defiance of purchasing rules imposed by Manila. 

   Last year, the accounting firm Price Waterhouse surveyed Dumanjug as part of a nationwide co-op analysis to pave the way for a $40 million USAID loan. 

   The accountants called his management structure top heavy, and frowned on his sawmill and prawn-farm schemes. 
Says Father Silva: "They felt the co-op} ran counter to sound management by all standards. 
And I agree with them. 
On paper, it looks bad. 

   "I had a hard time making them understand certain things I do." 

</TEXT>
