<HEAD>ABOARD THE MV BERLIN: Breves-Macacos channel.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``Like the Mississippi, the river is always changing,'' observed
first officer Andreas Jungblut, who has taken freighters up to
Baton Rouge, La. ``But in the Amazon there are no buoys or channel
markers, except for a rare light marking a sharp bend.''
   ``At least,'' adds Capt. Biehl, ``there are no bridges to worry
about all the way to Peru.''
   Flocks of yellow-bellied birds called bem-ti-vi, ``I see you,''
dart along the shore, and baldheaded vultures with enormous
wingspreads glide lazily overhead in the faint equatorial air
currents. The sailor on bow watch spots a trio of red freshwater
dolphins frisking just ahead.
   Night brings the telegraph-wire whine of cicadas, the shrieking
of nocturnal dourcouli monkeys, a sudden boom of thunder or another
falling tree, a solitary silver nighthawk soaring beneath the
Southern Cross and, so the first mate insists, the mating yowl of a
jaguar.
   Sunrise finds some passengers down on all fours photographing
the huge moths, fat beetles and slant-faced grasshoopers attracted
to our decks. A barman shimmies up the radio mast to pin a mammoth
purple and gold butterfly for his collection.
   Before noon, the city of Santarem, 700 miles from the sea,
breaks the monotony of forest and savanna. Settled by Confederate
veterans of the Civil War, this gateway to the gold fields has
false-front cafes right out of the American West, signboarded with
names like Higgins, Jackson and MacDonald.
   A torrential downpour cancels a barbecue at Alter do Chao, a
nearby pink ribbon of beach. Then a rainbow arches over the river,
and the Berlin lowers her motor launches so passengers can swim in
the Amazon and walk out for nearly a mile on a narrow, curling
sandbar.
   ``Where have all the piranhas gone?'' an elderly lady inquires.
   ``Fled for their lives,'' answers ship's surgeon Heinz Wehselau.
   Next morning the boats are lowered again for a visit to Boca de
Valeria, a native village of thatched huts on stilts and a red mud
trail through tangled wetlands teeming with exotic flowers,
brilliantly plumed birds and strange insects, like a 4-inch-long
crawling something brightly banded in black and yellow with a red
head and tail. The landing party returns with bows and arrows,
spears and a variety of tick and mosquito bites.
   Some 1,200 miles up river, just below Manaus, nature stages a
spectacular for the film buffs on board. On our left, the
coffee-brown Solimoes River, flowing a mile wide out of lush
lowlands, meets the broad black Rio Negro, fed far upstream by the
snows of the Andes.
   For a dozen miles they flow side by side without mingling, like
competing oil slicks. The banks of the Solimoes swarm with leeches
and insects, while the Rio Negro is almost pest free.
   ``Even the fish swim aloof in their different colored
currents,'' the Brazilian pilot informs us.
   The two eventual mix at the ``Wedding of the Waters'' to form
the Amazon's final surge to the sea.
   At Manaus, the Berlin ties up to the floating dock built by
British engineers at the turn of the century and assembled piece by
piece to accommodate the 45-foot rise and fall of the river.
   The custom house and ``Little Ben,'' the clock chiming in the
plaza before the cathedral, also were prefabricated in Europe in
the days when rubber was king and Manaus glittered like the El
Dorado dreamed of by the conquistadors.
   Workmen were busy restoring the Italian frescoes in the
gold-domed Teatro Amazonas, the 1,000-seat opera house that
showcased Jenny Lind, the Ballet Russe and string quartets playing
Liszt for the rubber barons, whose decaying mansions are now
subdivided into tenements. In 1910, Manaus boasted French modistes,
British tailors, 15 miles of streetcar track and cafes with
fountains gushing champagne.
   Such luxury in the middle of a rain forest was purchased at a
terrible price in human suffering. The Indians who tapped the white
latex from the wild rubber trees were kept in virtual peonage by
their white and mestizo patrones.
   Penned up at night, underpaid for their labor, overcharged at
the company store, often sick with malaria and dengue fever, the
tappers were kept to a quota by guards armed with clubs and guns.
The first failure to meet the quota resulted in a beating. The
tapper lost an ear for the second failure, his other ear for the
third and was killed for the fourth.
   International commissions met to protest the brutality. Then
Henry Wickham, a British biologist, solved the problem by smuggling
out seeds of the wild rubber tree to the royal botanical gardens at
Kew for cultivation as a plantation crop in the Malaysian states.
   By 1915, the boom was over. Cheaper, Asian rubber dominated the
market. Manaus receded to a town on stilts at the water's edge with
suburbs of ``flutuantes,'' floating houses, as the rain forest
reclaimed the cobblestone streets leading to the candy-colored
villas on the cliffs.
   But now with an oil refinery, a 60,000-ton steel plant, huge
sawmills and government-decreed duty-free shops to bolster its
economy, Manaus is making a comeback. Jumbo jets fly in daily from
Miami and Rio.
   The sprawling Tropical Hotel, cleared from the jungles along the
Rio Negro, is attracting conventions from around the world, along
with jet setters and Antwerp diamond dealers to its arcade of
boutiques and jewelry stores.
   At the height of the rubber boom, 400 passenger ships a year
left Liverpool for Manaus.
   ``Two or three cruise ships a month call here now, but we are
hoping for many more,'' says Godfrey Springer from Tooting Bec
outside of London who settled in the Amazon with his Brazilian
wife. He makes his living taking tourists up the side creeks of the
Solimoes in a frail putt-putt boat to view crocodiles lurking among
the Victoria Regia lily pads, broad enough for a small, brave child
to use as a float for sun bathing.
   One would think that like Joseph Conrad's hero, Mr. Kurtz, the
natives would cry, ``the horror, the horror,'' at the first sight
of tourists invading the heart of their dark rain forest. Instead
they smile and offer snakeskin handbags and masks made of turtle
shells that will certainly be confiscated by U.S. Customs agents.
   The Amazon indeed has seen it all.
</TEXT>
