<HL> Environmentalists in Brazil Mobilize In Bid to Save Once-Vast Atlantic Forest </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> LATAM </CO>
<IN> ENV </IN>
<DATELINE> RIO DE JANEIRO (AP)  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Environmentalists are mobilizing to save what is left of Brazil's once-vast Atlantic forest, the nation's picture-postcard front door. 

   One of the species of trees near extinction is the brazilwood, or pau-Brazil, which gave the country its name. 

   When Portuguese explorers discovered Brazil in 1500, the Atlantic forest covered about 170,000 square miles along a 3,000-mile coastal strip. 

   Today, with 80 million of the country's 143 million people and most of its heavy industry crowded into the coastal zone, only about 3% of the original primary forest remains -- in scattered patches. 

   Some of the forest's rare monkeys, birds and trees, many found nowhere else in the world, face extinction. 

   "We are in the process of destroying an entire ecosystem, but there's still time to save what's left and prevent total tragedy," said Rodrigo Lara Mesquita, the chairman of a group called the S.O.S. Atlantic Forest Foundation. 

   The foundation has strong economic and political influence. 

   Mr. Mesquita is an heir of the family that for a century has controlled the influential O Estado de S. Paulo newspaper and media group. 
Others running S.O.S. include two multimillionaire industrialists, the president of the country's largest university and a retired admiral. 

   Since 1986, the foundation has raised the equivalent of more than US$4 million for nationwide newspaper and television publicity. 
It intends to collect more, for the satellite mapping of the forest zone and for conservation programs where the remaining forest is thickest. 

   "This group is powerful and well organized," said Russell A. Mittermeier, international vice chairman of the Washington-based World Wildlife Fund and a consultant to the Atlantic Forest organization. 
"It's not radical, as unfortunately was the case with many well-meaning but ineffective environmental groups that sprang up in the United States in the 1960s. 
I'm very optimistic." 

   Mr. Mittermeier has been traveling to Brazil since 1971, principally to work with the Atlantic forest's endangered monkey species. 

   He said in an interview in Rio de Janeiro that Brazil probably has the best chance for success of the "three highest-priority ecological problems in the world" -- the tropical South American Andes in Colombia, Ecuador and Peru; the African island of Madagascar; and the Atlantic forest. 

   "Here in the Atlantic forest, it really is possible to save the remnants," Mr. Mittermeier said. 
He mentioned specifically the muriqui, South America's largest primate, of which fewer than 100 remain; the Golden Lion Tamarin, another endangered monkey, with about 400 left; the increasingly scarce red-tailed parrot; the rare and valuable jacaranda tree; and the almost extinct pau-Brazil. 

   "Today, with few exceptions, the only place you can still see pau-Brazil is in a botanical garden," Mr. Mesquita said. 

   Early Portuguese pioneers chopped down all the brazilwood they could find to extract dye. 
Later settlers hacked away the coastal forest to make way for sugar cane and coffee plantations and for settlements. 

   The S.O.S. Atlantic Forest Foundation's logotype is a stylized green, yellow and blue Brazilian flag, but with part of the green ripped away. 

   A foundation poster shows a map of Brazil with an outline of the Atlantic forest as it existed in 1500, with the words, in Portuguese, "I Used to Be Like This." 
Then there is a map showing the scattered forest pockets left today and the words, "I Wound Up Like This." 

   The foundation's first specific project is to be in a still relatively untouched forest zone covering 3,500 square miles along the coasts of the southeastern states of Sao Paulo and Parana. 
It intends to set up two ecological bases and buy a patrol-type boat to sound the alarm against illegal tree cutting and the banned netting of coastal fish, shrimp and oysters. 

   "Invasion of that region has long gone unpunished," S.O.S. Chairman Mesquita said. 
"But we think we can stop it. 
We're organized, we've got money, and we have access to the authorities and the media." 

   The foundation also supported lobbying efforts in Brazil's congress to place in the draft of a new constitution the legal concept of "ecological crime." 

   "We're also attempting a process of environmental education," said Ibsen de Gusmao Camara, the former admiral who now is a member of the S.O.S board. 
"A lot of Brazilians think development automatically means physical occupation. 
It's not that they purposely want to destroy the environment. 
They just don't know any better." 

   "We'll never see the Atlantic forest again as it once was," he added. 
"That's impossible. 
But we will put a stop to the destruction and preserve and build up the forest's 'genetic library.'" 

