<CAPTION>  Photos (2), Map; PHOTO: Catherine M. Senecal; Villagers along the Zaire River
lash their canoes to a barge and climb aboard for a visit.; PHOTO: Catherine
M. Senecal -- Special to the Mercury News; Above, boys paddle their dugout
canoe to catch up with a fast-moving barge in Zaire. (color); MAP:
Knight-Ridder News Service; Zaire  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  TRAVEL; RIVER; ZAIRE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IN THE middle of Pygmy territory, slightly south of the Sudan and west of the
Ugandan border, I spent three hot, grueling days in the back of a beer truck
as it lurched down a severely pot-holed track through the jungle to Kisangani.
Kisangani was no haphazard destination for those of us on the truck. The
driver, for one, was delivering two goats to his uncle and taking 150 empty
cases of beer bottles for refilling. I was meeting the Zaire River barge to
repeat the last half of H.M. Stanley's journey of 100 years ago, when he
became the first known person to travel the river from its source to the
Atlantic Ocean -- some 1,400 miles downstream.;   After three days on the
road, however, my goals became less lofty, and I wanted only to eat, sleep and
wash up, not necessarily in that order. When we finally arrived, the driver
dropped my traveling companion and me off in front of the Olympia Hotel.
Although slightly decrepit-looking, the place was no less than a vision to us.
We checked in, washed up, wolfed down a plate of spanakopita and went to bed.
Two days later, we were on the barge along with 1,000 or so other passengers
as it pulled away from the bank and blew its final hoot.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  RIVERS LESS TRAVELED
AMID MONKEY MEAT AND EEL, A ZAIRE BARGE RIDER
DISCOVERS THAT AN EXPLORER'S STEAMY ROUTE EMBRACES
A LIFE OF BUY AND SELL  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cruise Special: Rivers; See also related stories on P. 1T and 5-11T of this
section; Additional information attached to the end of this article;
Free-lance writer Catherine M. Senecal lives in Winnipeg, Manitoba.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Squeezed onto five barges lashed together to a length of about one city
block and a width of 16 yards, the crowds on board looked like a chaotic
assembly of movie extras. For 10 days, this floating oddity hauled us from
Kisangani -- traveling past masses of tangled equatorial forest next to
limestone cliffs and rolling plains -- to Kinshasa, Zaire's capital, and the
river mouth leading to the Atlantic Ocean.;   I woke early the first morning
on the barge so I would have ample time to explore. Narrow hallways outside
the second-class cabins and on the lower decks became flourishing markets.
Business people set up miniature stalls and sold black-market penicillin,
malaria pills, peanuts or jewelry.;   This constant buying and selling proved
to be the prime entertainment over the next 10 days. Except at larger towns,
the barge rarely stopped. Instead, villagers paddled up to the barge, canoes
piled high with the specialty of their village -- bananas, avocados, dried
monkey meat, freshly shot antelope, bamboo chairs. To catch up to the
fast-moving barge, they stood to paddle. With babies on their backs and their
hair a mass of wired pigtails, merchant women paddled in, grabbed railings and
began to barter even before stepping on board. At times, as many as 100 canoes
were attached to the boat.;   The bartering reached chaotic proportions. Most
Zairians spoke French, the official language, and one or two of the other
major languages: Tshiluba Kikongo or Kiswahili. But for business transactions
on the river barge, people spoke Ungala, the language of the river. Sellers
yelled out offers. Potential buyers responded with disbelieving guffaws. Women
rolled their eyes and threw their hands in the air at especially ludicrous
prices. More than once, I stepped outside my cabin door in the middle of the
night to see what the racket was about. Nothing -- this was normal life here
on the barge.;   Haircuts and hand lotion; Once a villager sold all the
bananas, palm wine or whatever filled his canoe, he stepped on board, bought
cigarettes and razor blades, and maybe got a haircut from the resident barber.
Women bought cloth, soap, sugar, rice, and might treat themselves to a bottle
of hand lotion. Afterward, they paddled back to their villages, which were by
then miles upstream.;   We went first class, mainly because we wanted more
than the one meal a day offered in second or third class. Also, sleeping in a
cabin seemed like a good idea. Third-class passengers established territory
anywhere they found two square yards of space. A first-class room was about 6
by 6 feet with two narrow cots, a small shower and a toilet. The rooms were
air-conditioned erratically throughout the afternoon and night. (Even at six
in the morning, the temperature hovered at a humid 90.);   Zaire is one
massive river basin filled with forest and the Zaire River arcing its way
almost 3,000 miles from the south up and across the equator and back down. So
not surprisingly, most transportation is via the river on riverboats, ferries,
tugs or pirogues, canoes made of hollowed-out trees. Shortly after Stanley's
journey, the Belgians opened a trade route up the Zaire into Kisangani and
other villages deep within that area to ship out rubber and ivory. Later,
Zaire became a major slave market for Belgium's King Leopold.;   For many on
board, this trip was not a journey, but a job. Raja and Antoine rode back and
forth between Kisangani and Kinshasa selling combs and other toiletry items on
the barge. Other sellers collected goods in the country and hauled them to the
capital, Kinshasa. Onions hauled there fetched 10 times what they cost in the
rural areas. Goats, chickens -- even crocodiles -- were hauled alive. Chicks
and baby crocodiles were cooked and eaten as a snack. Commodities needing
preservation were singed and dried over a charcoal stove, such as monkey meat,
or sun-baked and stacked in baskets, such as eels.;   European-style meals
were served in the first-class dining lounge. The cook baked freshly caught
capitaine fish, or served roast beef with potatoes and gravy -- a rare treat
in Zaire. The bazaar-bedecked third-class area served its own fast-food fare.
You could start with grubs, live or barbecued, as an appetizer, washed down
with a weak beer, then walk to the next stall for sardines, cooked in a hot
pepper sauce, and then, round off the meal with a couple of sweet doughnuts
deep-fried before you. One evening, after lengthy soul-searching, I tried
fresh monkey meat -- a common Zairian meal. It tasted like tender stew meat.; 
 Dance beneath a setting sun; Every night, music floated from the dance hall
-- an odd combination of American rock and African chanting. When we didn't go
dancing, we climbed a ladder to the barge's rooftop, settled onto our portable
bamboo stools (bought on Day One from a villager), and prepared for the
evening show -- the setting sun. Near the equator, it appeared large and
glowed pink, then orange, before dipping down into a yolky haze. We welcomed
the cooling blackness as much as the captain disliked it. (Navigating the
river at night was tricky, and at times impossible.);   Just north of the
equator lies Mbandaka, a major point along the route where the Zaire River
meets the Ubangui, one of its tributaries. It was the sixth night of our
journey, and Raja, Antoine, my friend and I decided to go for a drink in town.
Sitting around a table outdoors, we talked late into the night about the
differences between Zaire and North America, not knowing when the whistle
would blow and signal us to make a mad dash for the departing barge.;   As it
turned out, it didn't leave till the next morning. I sat on the deck outside
my door and watched the morning fog rise to expose pockets of bamboo stalks
along the riverbank. I realized I was anxious to arrive in Kinshasa. I was
traveling in relative luxury compared to most people on the barge, but the
drain of being on a floating hotel with 999 other "guests" started to take
effect.;   Night's revealing lights; Late on the ninth day, the captain
anchored in Stanley's Pool -- a 15-by-20-mile bulge in the river. In place of
palm and towering limbo trees, rolling hills and grazing land surrounded me.
The selling slowed and passengers prepared to get off the boat. Night came as
we waited, revealing the lights of Kinshasa and Brazzaville, capital of the
Congo. The widening of the river suggested we were near the Atlantic Ocean,
yet we were still 300 miles inland.;   The next morning, we headed into the
port of Kinshasa. It felt good to walk on land again. We flagged a taxi to
take us to Hotel aux Canaries, close to the night food stalls and dancing
establishments.;   In the lobby, we met travelers who asked us about our
recent barge journey. They listened intently as my friend recounted sights
that to me now seemed commonplace. I stared off into one of the far corners of
the lobby and thought of the people who make that river journey -- back and
forth, back and forth.; If you go . . .; (check) ENTRY -- Zaire requires entry
visas for all foreign travelers. Write to the Embassy of the Republic of
Zaire, 18 Range Road, Ottawa, Ontario; or 1800 New Hampshire Ave. N.W.,
Washington, D.C. 20009. Foreign currency must be declared on entry into Zaire
and on departure, with official exchange proof for the difference.;   (check)
INFORMATION -- For tourism information, contact the Office National du
Tourisme, Immeuble de la Rwindi, blvd du 30 juin, BP 9502, Kinshasa 1, Zaire.;
  (check) RIVERBOATS -- For information on riverboats, write to the Office
National des Transports au Zaire (ONATRA) BP 1228, Kinshasa 1, Zaire,
telephone 22109. Boat service schedules change frequently. Contact the office
first before making firm plans to go.;   First-class barge tickets cost about
$89 (U.S.) for 10 days. Second and third class are inexpensive, but go first
class for comfort. In addition to the two cots, private toilet, shower, and
irregular air-conditioning, you get three meals a day, and a large padlock.;  
(check) READING -- Before or during the journey, read "The River Congo: The
Discovery, Exploration &amp; Exploitation of the World's Most Dramatic River" by
Peter Forbath (Houghton Mifflin). (The Zaire River is known as the Congo
outside Zaire.);   (check) WHEN TO GO -- The best time to go is from November
to March. Expect temperatures between 80 and 90 degrees and high humidity with
more rain south of the equator.;   -- Catherine M. Senecal  </TEXT>
